text: Okay by why was someone videotaping her shooting herself in the face?  I mean I know it was liveleak but still, you see a girl pull out a gun and your first instinct is to start filming? ¬†Oh wait I guess they just already happened to be filming because everyone is always filming random stuff at high school, amirite?  Can the whole found footage/horror genre just die already? ¬†It's always so unbelievable save maybe the first Paranormal Activity that it completely destroys any immersion it's able to create in the first place. ¬†This looks like it could be fun but I'm willing to bet it's going to be 100% jump scares, no actual atmosphere that lasts more than a minute, and a couple high school drama and love plots thrown in there. ¬†Don't even get me started on how this idea has already been done quite a few times..

text: I feel like this is more of a psychological horror. Of course, this is extreme and wouldn't happen, but it's sort of teaching a lesson (at least I imagine it does). Teaching a lesson that doing that kinda stuff (posting the video, going along with the bullying) can hurt you very badly down the road, as well as the others around you.  Also, I imagine they aren't just logging off or anything because they feel trapped by whatever or whoever is threatening them. Obviously they're pretty skeptical of the guy until shit starts happening that they can't explain, unless it's some elaborate, sick prank. Also, it's kinda scary because I feel like "billie"'s motive is to get the person to admit what they've done, and until they do, they have to watch their friends crumble in front of them. The billie guy is going to torture them until he gets the answer he wants, and none of them are owning up to it. The people who try to leave or cheat whatever is supposed to be happening to them, I believe that's where we start seeing some deaths.  I'm not the best at explaining my point but I hope this is understandable, and it seems like it has a lot of potential to be good!

text: Since i dont know what to post here, i think it'll be helpful to post a delicious pancake recipe.  Malt, rather than sugar, is what sweetens most food-service (i.e., restaurant/hotel) pancake mixes. For that typical "diner" taste, try malt in your pancakes instead of sugar.  Volume ¬† Ounces ¬† Grams 2 large eggs 1 1/4 cups milk 3 tablespoons melted butter or vegetable oil 1 1/2 cups King Arthur Unbleached All-Purpose Flour 3/4 teaspoon salt 2 teaspoons baking powder 2 tablespoons sugar OR 1/4 cup malted milk powder *Use 1 cup milk if you're baking under hot, humid conditions, or if you're going to let the batter rest longer than 15 minutes. Use up to 1 1/4 cups milk in cold, dry conditions. tips from our bakers To make waffles, substitute 2 tablespoons melted butter or vegetable oil for 2 tablespoons of the milk. Cook waffles as directed with your waffle iron. Hint - if you try to open the iron and it doesn't open easily, the waffle isn't done yet. For a whole grain breakfast treat, replace 1/2 cup of the all-purpose flour with 1/2 cup of ground oats. A grated apple mixed into the batter will keep the pancakes moist longer if you need to cook them ahead and bring them to the table all at once For blueberry pancakes, sprinkle fresh or thawed frozen blueberries over the batter after you pour it on the griddle. Mixing frozen blueberries into the batter before scooping will turn it blue and streaky. directions see this recipe's blog ¬ª 1. Beat the eggs and milk until light and foamy, about 3 minutes at high speed of a stand or hand mixer. Stir in the butter or vegetable oil.  2. Whisk the dry ingredients together to evenly distribute the salt, baking powder and sweetener.  3. Gently and quickly mix into the egg and milk mixture. Let the batter rest for at least 15 minutes, while the griddle is heating; it"ll thicken slightly.  4. Heat a heavy frying pan over medium heat, or set an electric griddle to 375¬∞F. Lightly grease frying pan or griddle. The pan or griddle is ready if a drop of water will skitter across the surface, evaporating immediately.  5. Drop 1/4 cupfuls of batter onto the lightly greased griddle. Bake on one side until bubbles begin to form and break, about 2 minutes; then turn the pancakes and cook the other side until brown, about 1 1/2 to 2 minutes. Turn over only once. Serve immediately.  Yield: 1 dozen large (4 1/2") pancakes  nutrition information Serving Size: One 4-inch pancake Servings Per Batch: 12 Amount Per Serving: Calories: 100 Calories from Fat: 40 Total Fat: 4g Saturated Fat: 2g Trans Fat: 0g Cholesterol: 40mg Sodium: 260mg Total Carbohydrate: 14g Dietary Fiber: 0g Sugars: 4g Protein: 4g

text: People are unaware that whenever you post something online, it's there forever whether you want it up or not. Sure the events in this movie didn't actually happen, but it doesn't matter. You guys are criticizing this movie before actually watching it. Saying it's stupid to have a movie in Skype format, but that's today's society. We revolve around technology and social networking, whether we like it or not. Also small words or actions can hurt someone and could cause them to commit suicide. This movie reminds me of a movie I've watched sort of about the same thing except not with Skype. You guys think it's stupid to have this, but to be completely honest this scares the hell out of me. Having someone who's been dead asking for a Skype call. Fuuuuuuuuuuck that. Lol.

author: Adam.

text: I'm not one to condemn a movie I've not seen yet, but some thoughts occur:  1| Why her friends? What causes her to go straight to the people close to her? I mean, if they're her friends, and care for her safety, why would it be them she goes to first in her little spree? They can't have been the only ones present during that. 2| The motive seems wonky. I mean yeah, she was a cruel bully in her life, and it would only seem logical that someone like that would take it out on the people around her. But why? Is it to avenge herself? _She's_ the one who took her own life about a temporary problem, so that doesn't seem fitting. 3| The message seems hammered-home. Yes, it is a good message: cyberbullying affects so many people, and it can even psychologically harm said people who bully into doing irreversible damage to themselves or others. As people, we need to know that what we think is harmless can hurt people in ways that aren't just physical. I just wish it didn't feel so forced in this case. 4| This may seem like a bit of a low blow, but has Universal actually been well-considered for their quality in recent years? It looks okay, but the voice acting seems a bit hammy and phoned-in. If it's planned as a B-Movie horror flick, I'm cool with that; a little cheese never hurts now and then. But I just hope this movie doesn't try to take itself too seriously.

I hate how everything around us is evolving into the media everyone uses, showing that this is our future, our world, and what we will forever be known for. When the next era comes along our century is going to be the biggest joke in history. ...Or it will just get worse and in history class the release date of the 1st iPhone will be on exams. text: I think this movie is based on Rehtaeh Parsons and Audrey Potts suicides. (Yes, I know Laura is a fake person) It's basically the same telling. Laura is at a party with drunk teenage boys and girls. Rehtaeh and Audrey were at a party with drunk teenage boys and girls. Laura was either raped/drunk. Rehtaeh and Audrey were both raped/sexual harassed by 3 drunk teenage boys. Laura received revolting comments,text messages and posts about the way she acted at the party. Both Rehtaeh and Audrey received stupid messages and were called sluts/hoes. ALL of them tried/committed suicide(Rehtaeh went into coma for her hanging and turned off her life support machine on April 7th 2014) and did end up dying. I think it's nice that people are showing their concerns through movies and such, but a making a movie precisely based on both of these 2 girls and then continuing the movie with some stupid crap is revolting. What Universal/every other movie producer should do is focus on the real and important things about these girls death and take that thing and mold it into something carrying and informational to everybody. For example, Cyber bully. That movie stated the topic, showed the ways to deal with it, showed how to get help and also showed the consequences of your actions. It may have been educational, but it was also entertaining and fun. That's what these kind of movies should be telling. (And no, this isn't coming from some concerned mom who goes onto YT and talks sense without getting replies and thumbs up, this is coming from a concerned teenager who has witnessed a friend commit suicide in front of her.)

text: I couldn't even watch the whole trailer. ¬†It wasn't scary-I was just feeling too embarrassed for whoever made this film.  No thanks Universal. ¬†I don't want to watch another cash grab. ¬†If it were a small time director, I would be more supportive, but this is just so bad.  First of all, nobody cares that these people die. ¬†In fact, that's what we want to happen! ¬†They are all snobby teenagers who bullied someone into suicide. ¬†It won't scare us, we'll just be disappointed at a lack of visuals. ¬†We want to see that fat kid's arm get blended and for the others to like get.... skinned alive or something. ¬†Nobody is going to care about these characters.  We care about characters like Sarah Connor, Ellen Ripley, Luke Skywalker, Indiana Jones or Ian Malcolm. ¬†Sure not all of characters weren't in horror movies, but you didn't want them dead. ¬†This allowed you to be moved emotionally when shit hit the fan.  This is like Sharknado in that it's embarrassing, but nothing over-the-top stupid happens because it's only just a Skype call.  Sharknado involved blowing up tornados in the most retarded fashion you can think of, while this involves talking nice to some ghost chick on Skype so she "sees the light" or some shit and leaves you alone. ¬†Then the main character dies or something so they can do a sequel.

text: This movie looks like a pathetic attempt to cash in on modern technology, and reading the comments, I am even more disappointed that people are actually taking this seriously and giving the filmmakers more credit than they deserve. "Don't like it, don't watch it." Well, I do not plan on watching this movie. "Watch the movie first before you comment on it." Well, unfortunately, I believe the trailer says enough about the movie for me to know that I will not waste my time watching this. As for why I commented on the video, well, I actually value my opinion enough to share it. This is not a "new genre of horror"; this is an insult to a genre and a middle finger to all the predecessors before it. When your trailer has me laughing at how cheap and terrible it looks, and then I see people actually thinking that this "thing" is something salvageable, I immediately have to be that guy that just says, "No. No. This movie does not look good or interesting. No."

text: We are all gathered here today to pay our respects. This thriving, innovative and beautiful creativity that we call cinema, has passed away. It had a joyful and wonderful start as does most things on this earth but just like most things on this earth, it came to a tragic end. Cinema lost it's passion, desire and will by rehashing the same work it had been drawn to in the beginning. Following formulas, studios pushing other film makers out of the industry and paving the way for great ideas to be crushed by what you see above. As we say farewell let us be reminded of the passion that it brought to us, the ideas and the joy. Rest in peace cinema, rest in peace. May you rise again such as a phenoix from the ashes.

text: This is new. I like the idea, an original one btw,¬†mostly because people *do* kill themselves¬†because they were bullied¬†or¬†cyber-bullied.¬†I'm rooting for the killer here, screw the other characters.¬†At least with other horror movies, you root for at least 1 or 2 people to survive. Maybe you like horror characters like Freddy Kruger, or want the douchebag characters to die, but you never root for the killer.  I don't remember a whole lot of horror movies¬†where you root for the killer. The only other horror that I can think of where you root for the killer,¬†is Carrie, but she wasn't a killer throughout the film, just near the end when the bullies spilled the pig blood on her, and made her snap.  The power this ghost has, its best *not* to question it. Seriously, I see people in this comment section questioning how this ghost can kill people through Skype, yet powers to kill people in their dreams, a spell to transfer souls into dolls, and a damn¬†leprechaun that kills people over gold he has no use for, and other goofy horror stuff,¬†is apparently ok.  I'd like to see this concept used more often, and this will *definitely* scare the shit out of actual cyberbullies, and make them paranoid as fuck.

text: Wait, i heard that this movie was based on a true story? I don't think so. There was a real story about a girl who's mistakes and personal stuff got leaked on to the interent, after that she drank a lot of bleach and then hung herself which is really sad. But that's it, that's the story. They should of said that this movie was inspired by the story, not based on it. A movie inspired by a true story to me at least means that the movie took the idea of the actual event that happened and made it into their own movie. For example, the life of Ed Gein inspired the film The Texas Chainsaw Massacre. A movie BASED on a true story is basically one big feature length long high budget Dramatization. There is a difference. I hope this was informative. I did the best i could.

text: This is shameful. From what I've seen we've got a "review" from the same source twice, plus some other guy. A new genre of horror? New isn't always good, and I don't see what is new about a vengeful spirit using electronics for revenge. And then we've got...materialized blenders and TELEPORTATION? For Pete's sake! Ghosts are malevolent spirits, not omnipotent demons. Oh, and the deceased was a vicious bully, so what I'm seeing here is that she couldn't handle a taste of her own medicine. Unless they change the plot, we can also conclude the last woman in the video will be the uploader and then somehow be saved, or killed. Not to mention, the lazy, and will-be-most-likely-overused, camera cut-outs, camera shake and feed distortion in order to compensate for the lack of logical flow, even in the horror genre. I've lost faith in the horror genre a long time ago. Every executive thinks the natural reaction to shock terror means that people are really terrified by it. Sometimes the fact that the evil in the movie DOESN'T act often and remains a constant threat to be feared is the scariest.  This is one movie I won't be seeing, even in the second-run theaters, and if the rest of you had any common sense, you wouldn't either.
author: Marsha Oakley

text: I don't understand why so much people are giving so many stupid advices on the movie.  EXAMPLE: "Close skype." "Turn off laptop." Let me point out that in the Wiki of this movie, it CLEARLY SAYS that when you LOG OFF OR GET AWAY FROM THE SCREEN AND AREN'T INTERACTING WITH THE CALL WHATSOEVER, You will fucking die. So, let's say that spooky ghost came in my skype. Here's things I shouldn't do, or I am dead. 1. Close skype 2. Hide somewhere without the laptop or device with the skype call 3. Turn off the devices If you are away from the call, you're fucked. Got that? Good. Now shut the fuck up, and get hyped for the movie, because this is actually original, and very good in my opinion. A few flaws would that I would include is WHOS COMPUTER IS PLAYING DURING THE MOVIE. Like, who's behind the computer of the screen you're seeing. It's kinda odd just seeing everyone else but yourself. But, I'm guessing it's the last girl, since she was still standing, or laura herself. Everything else is exquisite and brilliant! This movie is sure to bring new genre into future movies. 9/10 Can't wait for it to be released.

text: Im surprised that people are saying ''This is the most orginal movie I seen.'' granted the plot is somewhat different but the style they display it isnt. It has the making of standard jump scares and the title doesnt make sense at all but before I go on SPOILER ALERT, well not really since they gave out 90% of the plot away in the trailer (tell tell sign of a novice director). The original name for this film when it was shown at a film festival a year ago is Cybernatural, which makes more sense since they were never actaully friends. Laura was the standard popular girl who also bullies but things get reversed after the video was uploaded. The ''unpopular kids'' aka the group in the movie harassed her the most because everyone else was doing it now. For those who are saying that ''This is a anti cyberbullying film!'' Its not really true. Sure most movies like these are about bullying if you think hard enough but this is not a PSA. The director stated on the wiki page for the film he is already planning on making several sequals, his intentions is more of a line of making a revenge and gore film which explains the blender scene. The plot seems odd too. Why does she wait a year? Why didnt she seeked help? The best I can make sense of this is either she wanted to wait until the anniversary of her death to take revenge or she spent all this time spying on them and plotting. My best guest for her not seeking help is probably she either felt there was no hope for her or maybe she just didnt know where to turn (it does happen) but now thats just assumptuons. Sorry for the lengthy comment, I found this on imdb first and I wanted to see why most critics gave it positive reviews. This seems like just another horror movie.

text: I've seen the movie there was a prescreening at USC Columbia and after watching the movie i can honestly say it is not as bad as some people are saying it will be. I did not go into the movie expecting a scary movie and it was not scary in the least, however, the movie was surprisingly very funny with clever use of the computer screen interface that the viewer is watching throughout the movie, relatable and interesting characters, and a good sense of humor. True this is supposed to be a horror movie, but i think everybody knew this would not be scary so when watching, just expect to have a few laughs rather than screams. Id say it is not worth watching in theaters, however when it comes out on RedBox give it a rent and have some fun with your friends.   Also, about the notion of "turning off skype", the movie plays with that idea and shows why they don't leave. Props to the movie for that. Also it should be said that the movie is different from the trailer, many scenes shown in the trailer will not be seen in the actual movie, such as the guy getting run over by the car. I actually found this enjoyable because then i didn't know everything that was going to happen and how it would happen.

text: Universal Pictures, I appreciate that you're dumping money into the laps of Youtube and several of the content providers I regularly enjoy. I'm sure they're grateful for that as well. That said, making your commercial unskippable only sows enmity in me and instills in me a burning desire to avoid your film, particularly after I have seen one of the trailers for the 400th time. Consider in the future, making the commercial skippable at a certain mark. Perhaps, if you are insistent we watch the whole trailer, then make an adjustment after the first week or two of promotion that would allow us to skip the ad. I am personally TIRED of seeing it. I don't know if annoying people is good press but it just makes me want to go get an ad blocker. Thanks for your time, you have taken quite enough of mine, I'd appreciate your clemency in the future.

text: I am now going to point every problem (that i saw) in this trailer. It has a lot of time inconsistencies, as in the corner of the computer you can see the time that the scene is meant to take place. So ether the editing department took the year off, or they just cut random bits together. Make no mistake, there is more than what I mention here. here we go , the time goes from 9:21 pm, to 9:03 pm, to 9:22 pm, then back to 9:21 pm, (not even gonna touch on how the time for the "ghost‚Äù message ¬†is at ¬†12:01) THEN to 9:20, then back to 9:21 pm, then to 9:37 pm, then to 9:39 pm, then back to 9:21 pm, then to 9:36 pm, then they finally realize time goes forward and make it 9:47 pm, then forget it seconds later as the time is 9:34 pm. then 9:49, then 9:36. I didn‚Äôt even touch on the fact that at the very beginning, it said the video that caused her to commit suicide was uploaded on April 9th, but then later in the trailer, if you pause at the right moment, it says that video was uploaded on April 3rd. and finally, the plot-hole that sucks the movie in like a black hole, is in the trailer itself. The group of 6 meet up on the same day she died (how convenient) and she then comes into the call, somehow knowing it was one of those 6. And how she kills them? She takes over their minds (I guess) and makes them commit suicide. So, that raises the question of why doesn't she just read their minds and be done with it instead of killing 5 innocent people? oh yeah and how she fell forward after shooting herself in the head was BS. i dont have... the highest expectations for this movie, but if the whole movie is gonna be like this, they must have made a late April fools joke.

text: This trailer gave up the whole movie, I watched the movie yesterday.  But like some of the stuff in the trailer they said like "who posted the video" it didn't happen, and like the movie pissed me off, but good and really fucking scary I had nightmares. But yea the movie pissed me off, you gotta watch it to see why.   It was good, but short with no background at all.

I enjoyed it, despite what other movie goers may say, I'd recommend it to people. It's a new breed of horror and while I do admittingly wish that it took place in more locations than online on Facebook or Skype, it was still enjoyable. The characters each have a personality, and while they're not thoroughly fleshed out, they give you enough to know how each is. Laura is another type of scary after she died. She's the thing that will give you nightmares & appear afraid if you ever get on the internet and a random pop up message comes online. Can't wait for the sequels, hopefully no prequels.

text: I was so excited for this and yet it was shit. More funny than scary, the trailer is practically the movie. Literally the movie is how the trailer goes, they get into a Skype call, a random person is in it and they can't get rid of it (which I don't see why they wouldn't have just stopped skyping right then, while they still could). Laura is the person in the call, she threatens them and ginger girl is exposed then drinks bleach. She threatens them more, exposes them more, then they finally find a way to get her out of the call thanks to the fat guy. Then they stupidly keep skyping, which results in her coming back and killing the fat guy. She exposes them more and starts a never have I ever game and the loser dies. But first the guy with the gun gets something printed out and so does the main girl, each saying don't show them this or he/she dies. The other boy threatens to leave (which would result in him dying) if she doesn't show him, and she does show him and the boy gets shot. There's 3 left, more exposure, blonde girl gets locked in the room and gets a straightener down the throat. The main girl and guy are last, and Laura's last question is who uploaded the video, and at the last second of the countdown she admits it was him, so he gets stabbed in the eye. Then the ghost comes to the main girls house and kills her because it shows the end of the video that shows she's the one who took the video. There, just saved you an hour and 40 minutes of complete shit.

text: They could have done a lot better on this film. It had some potential, but they fucked up and since they only care about revenue, I had to count the mistakes on 2 hands.  For example, here is one of the flaws with the movie: - At one point, all people on Skype were supposed to keep their hand up to the camera, holding out their fingers. Then at the same time, the girl is typing very fast as if she was using 2 fingers. But all along, she only had 1 hand to work with.  ¬†Fucking lame.  Also, there are various points in the movie where they are using a loop of the person on Skype, and the same loop is used to portray them being connected on the video call, even though you can tell it was filmed at separate times.

text: Okay, so...  Let me rant about this, because some people are apparently confused. *[SPOILERS ALERT]*  First of all, turning off their computers, like most people are saying they should do, won't help.  The ghost is not IN their computers, it's just using that to communicate.  It can still kill them if they turned the computers off or ran away.  Second of all, you have to understand that movies can't explain every single detail of why what's happening is happening to you, that would be too boring, not how movies work. Specially in movies like Unfriended.  They leave a few things unanswered to leave the viewer thinking about the movie afterwards and it leaves some space for your imagination to take place, if you put a little effort into trying to figure out why what's happening is happening, you'll figure it out.  Third of all, the ghost already knows who did everything.  She's just after revenge and none of the people that were on there are innocent. They've all done their fair share to the dead girl, just because not everything was revealed of what they've done, it doesn't mean any of them were innocent, again, the ghost knows everything.  Here are some things that confused people and my answers to them: *Ken dying from the blender.* I know that it might seem like having your hand ripped up like that won't kill you, but if you actually search it up, or use common sense, it does kill you. There's veins there and he could die from blood loss and other things, and not only that, but he also got his throat cut up. So if his hand and wrist being ripped apart isn't enough to kill him, that surely would be.   *Ken freezing for a good two minutes looking at the camera.* He froze like that, staring because he either saw the ghost of Laura, the one that appeared at the end of the movie. Or he got possessed, or both.  Or he literally just spaced out for a a good two minutes, it's not so odd after all.  *The kids, or let's say, young adults, being alone.* It's not really that impossible! Adam mentioned he was home alone. Blaire's father was out, and she could only be living with him. I don't know about the rest of them but they could just be living alone, or they might not have siblings and they're parents aren't there, they look old enough.   And finally, why the heck are people complaining about how "unrealistic" this movie is? There are tons of movies out there, not all of them have to be oh so realistic to suit your highness's taste. Go watch reality shows or something if you want realistic.  If you don't believe in ghosts and such things as spirits, and hate movies with them so much. Simply do not watch the movie, is it that hard? Keep in mind that all movies are someone else's brilliant idea and people put effort into doing them, a lot of effort.  The least you can do is respect the hard work people put into it and move along if you don't like it.   To each person their own taste of everything.   *Takes a deep breath*  So, yush. :3

text: Ok so I just finished watching the movie and it was a good movie. Besides the haunting through Skype, I think it addressed and covered some real life shit. For example, cyber-bullying and the fact that you can't really trust anyone nowadays. However, I don't exactly think Laura had the right to take such actions. Did she have a right to be freaking angry? Hell yeah. But what she did was a no no, taking into consideration that she herself was pretty mean to like everybody and she probably did some messed up things to them too. Maybe it was never to the extent that Mitch went but then again, there's the issue of individuality; what may not hurt me may hurt AF to another individual. So yeah. Oh and, Blaire mentioned that Laura acted the way she did because she was going through some things. Well everybody is going through stuff in their lives. So if that excuse was good enough to give Laura a free pass then it's good enough for the rest of them. They were going through stuff and that's why they did what they did. My point? She had no right to take such actions. Now go rest in peace for God sake and stay rested. Lolz. Once again, good movie. :) Oh, if I die then that means that Laura caught some major feels about this comment... Now I'm scared to post it :'( Oh well. Here goes me exercising my freedom of speech :P

text: Spoiler: I like how this movie is realistic in a sense that people you wouldn't expect to lie, lie, but to a deeper depth will they keep that secret till the death of them. Blaire betrayed Mitch, and kept that from everybody. You could tell Blaire cheated from early on when the spirit of laura presented the file saying "not your boyfriend," and Blaire still kept her secrecy as well as everybody until they all knew of their demise. Laura wasn't only betrayed by everybody, but she was a product of people's want to defamate the character of others for their own enjoyment.  Yea I thought this movie was corny and I wouldn't watch it again because their is no point really, but I like the message it presented; people are disgusting and not to be trusted. text: Didn't bother to see this movie when it came out due to it looking retarded and what do you onow, I was right.  Attempted style over substance, unlikable characters ruining any investment in what happens to them, lack of atmospheric music, annoying computer sounds ruining the immersion, nothing creepy that plays on the psyche, lack of creepy visuals that could have been utilized, deaths that were as cheesey as  chocking yourself with your own hand reaching from just beyond the framing, relying too much on jump scares, and idiotic responses like holding a gun up to a web cam.  A horror definitely for the dull minded.  I could have shot a better horror film on this budget.  Sign's moronic aliens who are foiled by wooden doors and are weak against water were scarier and that isn't saying much in the vast world of horror movies.  2 out of 10 for this flop.  Waste you time with a better cheesey flick like sharknado...sigh.

text: Clever movie which describes how the ‚Äúextension‚Äô‚Äô and ‚Äúamplification‚Äô‚Äô of the virtual world progressively destroy our humanity, by dismantling our habitual and traditional mind structures, and create completely hypocritical, fake and superficial social interactions.   But if we stay very attentive, we could suggest that the movie goes even further than that, and allows a rather disturbing metaphysical interpretation. Unfriended proposes the idea that our immersion in the virtual world, which becomes stronger and stronger, ends up providing a real alive ¬´ essence ¬ª to virtuality itself. Unconsciously, we feed this essence while we dive more and more deeply into the virtual world. Through the time, energy and our various subjective fantasies and desires that we invest in the virtual world, we finally render the latter autonomous. Virtuality, now possessing a fully independent and self-relying essence, [spoiler alert] emancipates itself from its ancient master (the human) who has simply become obsolete, and destroys him/her in the most brutal and gruesome ways.
